  <div class="article-wrapper clearfix">
    <div class="main-content-column">
      <div class="text-wrapper" itemprop="articleBody">
        <p><a href="http://www.independent.co.uk/topic/george-w-bush">George W Bush's</a> chief ethics lawyer has said <a href="http://www.independent.co.uk/topic/jeff-sessions">Jeff Sessions</a>' denial he had contact with a Russian ambassador during the Presidential campaign was "a good way to go to jail".</p>

<p>Mr Sessions had two conversations with Sergey Kislyak during the campaign season but, at his confirmation hearing for the Attorney General post he now holds, told senators he "did not have communications with the Russians".</p>

<p>An early supporter of <a href="http://www.independent.co.uk/topic/donaldtrump">President Donald Trump</a> and a policy adviser to the Republican candidate, Mr Sessions had been asked what he would do if he discovered "anyone affiliated" with the campaign had been in contact with the Russian government. He has now been accused of <a href="http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/nancy-pelosi-jeff-sessions-attorney-general-lied-under-oath-resign-russian-envoy-donald-trump-a7607011.html">"lying under oath"</a> by Democrat Nancy Pelosi, the House minority leader.</p>

<p>Commenting on the revelations, ethics lawyer Richard Painter said: "Misleading the Senate in sworn testimony about [one's] own contacts with the Russians is a good way to go to jail."</p>

<div class="dnd-widget-wrapper context-sdl_editor_representation type-gallery"><div class="dnd-atom-rendered"><!-- scald=5194596:sdl_editor_representation --><div class="image"><script>
